Lab 01: Create user database

Purpose: Create a database to store usernames, passwords and their roles.

Task . Create the user database

Step Start the database. Create a database called app_users.

Enter:

  • Database Name: app_users
  • User Name: app
  • Password: app

Step Run the following script to create tables and insert user records.

Shortcut SHIFT+F6 to run the sql file.

CREATE TABLE USERS (
  USERID VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,
  PASSWORD VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,
  PRIMARY KEY (USERID)
);

CREATE TABLE USERS_GROUPS (
  GROUPID VARCHAR(20) NOT NULL,
  USERID VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,
	  PRIMARY KEY (GROUPID, USERID)
	);
	
	SELECT * FROM tabs WHERE table_name LIKE '%USER%';
	
	INSERT INTO USERS VALUES('john', '1234');
	INSERT INTO USERS VALUES('mary', '1234');
	INSERT INTO USERS_GROUPS VALUES('mis', 'john');
	INSERT INTO USERS_GROUPS VALUES('admin', 'mary');
	
COMMIT;

Task . Create a connection pool and a jndi name for the database in the app server

Step Start the glassfish server. Navigate to the Domain Admin Console page.

Step Navigate to: Resources > JDBC > JDBC Connection Pools

Create a new connection pool app_users with the following properties

  • SecurityMechanism = 3
  • User = app
  • Password = app
  • DatabaseName = APP_USERS

Step Navigate to Resource > JDBC > JDBC Resources.
Create a new JNDI name jdbc/app_users with the following property:

  • Pool Name: app_users

You can check the create jndi name in the Netbeans:

Lab 02: Create a JDBC Realm for container authentication using the app_users database

A Realm is the place that stores the Principals. The principal is the authenticated user in the container.

Step Navigate to the Domain Admin Console page.

Step Navigate to: Configurations > server-config > Security > Realms > (B)New

Step Enter the following:

  • Name = app_user_realm
  • Class Name = com.sun.enterprise.security.ee.auth.realm.jdbc.JDBCRealm
  • JAAS Context: jdbcRealm
  • JNDI: jdbc/app_users

Notes:

  • JAAS Context 是設定使用的 login module。Login module 定義在 /config/login.conf 中。JAAS Context 的欄位大小寫有差別，且字串要和 C:\glassfish4\glassfish\domains\domain1\config 中設定字串要相同
  • Glassfih 會使用 JNDI 欄位中的 JDBC DataSource 去取得資料庫連線。

Step 接續設定類別的和儲存使用者帳號、密碼及群組相關屬性資料庫表格資訊。告訴 Glassfish 儲放使用者帳號及密碼的表格、帳號欄位、密碼欄位名稱。另外，告訴 Glassfish 使用者群組及群組欄位名稱。

Step 接續設定 Password Encryption 及 Digest Algorithm。如果資料庫中的密碼使用 plain text，則 Password Encryption及 Digest Algorithm 皆設為 None。另外，Charset 也要設為 UTF-8 才可以正常運作。(換句話說，要和資料庫加密方式及編碼方式一致才可以正常運作。

Step Restart the Glassfish server to check if the real is created successfully

Lab 03: Map the Security Roles to Principals

完成 Glassfish 上的 JDBCRealm 上的設定後，接著要設定 glassfish-web.xml，將 web.xml 中設定的 Security Role 和 Container 内的 principal 或者 User Group 對應。

Step Open your application project: Ch14_SecureApp_Base.

Step Open the vendor (Glassfish) Deployment Descriptor file glassfish-web.xml. Navigate to: (T)Security > (B)Add Security Role Mapping.

Lab 04: Set up the From-Based Container Authentication

How it works:

Notes [2]:

  1. A client requests access to a protected resource.

  2. If the client is unauthenticated, the server redirects the client to a login page.

  3. The client submits the login form to the server.

  4. The server attempts to authenticate the user.

  • Case 1: If authentication succeeds, the authenticated user’s principal is checked to ensure it is in a role that is authorized to access the resource. If the user is authorized, the server redirects the client to the resource using the stored URL path.

  • Case 2: If authentication fails, the client is forwarded or redirected to an error page (with stats code 403 Forbidden).

Reference: https://docs.oracle.com/cd/E19226-01/820-7627/bncbq/index.html

容器表單驗證工作原理 [3]

Source: https://www.slideshare.net/JustinSDK/ch10-web

Tasks

  1. Create the Login, authentication failed (Status code 401), and not authorized (Status code 403) pages
  2. Configure the secured resources.

Task 1. Create the Login, authentication failed (Status code 401), and not authorized (Status code 403) pages

Step Create the folder /webroot/auth. Create the authmethodform.xhtml JSF page.

Step Use the masterLayout.xhtml as the template with the following codes:

<ui:composition template="/templates/masterLayout.xhtml">
</ui:composition>

Step Add <ui:define> to define the contents for the contentArea in the template.

Step Add the following codes inside the <ui:define> section:

<form method="POST" action="j_security_check">
    <div class="form-group">
        <label for="inputName"> User Name </label>  
        <input id="inputName" class="form-control" type="text" name="j_username"/>
    </div>
    <div class="form-group">
        <label for="inputPasswd"> Password </label>   
        <input id="inputPasswd" class="form-control" type="password" name="j_password"/>
        <input class="btn btn-primary" type="submit" value="Login"/>
    </div>
</form>

Note:

  • the action attribute in the form is set to j_security_check
  • the parameter names for the username and password should be j_username and j_password.

Step Add the badLogin.xhtml to webroot/auth:

<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8' ?>
<!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN" "http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd">
<html xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
      xmlns:h="http://xmlns.jcp.org/jsf/html">
    <h:head>
        <title>Bad Login</title>
    </h:head>
    <h:body>
        Incorrect user name or password.
    </h:body>
</html>

Step Add the notAllowed.xhtml to webroot/auth:

<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8' ?>
<!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN" "http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd">
<html xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
      xmlns:h="http://xmlns.jcp.org/jsf/html"
      xmlns:ui="http://xmlns.jcp.org/jsf/facelets">
    <h:head>
        <title>Not Allowed</title>
    </h:head>
    <h:body>
        <ui:composition template="/templates/masterLayout.xhtml">
            <ui:define name="contentArea">
            You entered a good user name and password but are not allowed to view the requested resource.
            <h:link class="btn btn-primary" outcome="/index">Home </h:link>
            </ui:define>
        </ui:composition>
    </h:body>
</html>

Step Open web.xhtml. Select (T)Security > Login Configuration.

Step Check the Form option and enter the following field values:

  • Form Login Page: /faces/auth/authmethodform.xhtml
  • Form Error Page: /faces/auth/badLogin.xhtml
  • Real Name: app_users_realm

Step Select (T)Page in the web.xml. Add the following values to set the error page for status code 403:

  • Error Code: 403
  • Error Page Location: /auth/notAllowed.xhtml

Step Select (T)Source in the web.xml. Change /auth/notAllowed.xhtml to /faces/auth/notAllowed.xhtml.

Lab 05: Create the logout link and show user name in the navigation bar

Task: Create the managed bean

Step Create the auth source package.

Step Create the JSF managed bean SecurityBean with the request scope.

Step Inject the Principal instance to principal field. The injected Principal instance represents the current caller.
In addition inject HttpServletRequest instance to request to represent the current request from the caller.

@Inject private Principal principal;
@Inject private HttpServletRequest request;

Step Create a method getPrincipalName to return the call name:

//If not logged in this returns "<anonymous>" on WLS
//If not logged in this returns "ANONYMOUS" on GF
public String getPrincipalName(){
        return principal.getName();
    }

Step Create a method isLoginStatus to check the if the user has logged in.

public boolean isLoginStatus() {
        String remoteUser  = request.getRemoteUser();
        return (remoteUser != null);
    }

Step Create a method logout() to let user logout its account.

public String logout() {
        try {
            request.logout();
        } catch (ServletException ex) {
            Logger.getLogger(SecurityBean.class.getName()).log(Level.SEVERE, null, ex);
        }
        return "/auth/authmethodform?faces-redirect=true";
    }

Step Create a method to check if the user is the admin role.

public boolean isAdmin(){
        ExternalContext context = FacesContext.getCurrentInstance().getExternalContext();
        return context.isUserInRole("admin");
    }

Task: Modify the navigation bar

Step Open webroot/templates/navbar.xhtml.

Step Make the Customer List link only render for admin role.

<ui:fragment rendered="#{securityBean.admin}">
    <li id="customerItem" class="active">
        <h:link outcome="/admin/customerList">Customer List</h:link> 
    </li>
</ui:fragment>

Step Make the username appear on the right of the navigation bar.

Step Add a logout action link to the right of the navigation bar.

The resultant right navigation bar codes:

<ul class="nav navbar-nav navbar-right">
    <li><a> <h:outputText value="#{securityBean.principalName}"  /> </a> </li>
    <ui:fragment rendered="#{securityBean.loginStatus}" >
        <li id="logoutAction"> 
            <h:commandLink action="#{securityBean.logout}" >
                <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-log-out"></span> Logout 
            </h:commandLink>
        </li>
    </ui:fragment>
</ul>

Step Make the Customer List link in the left sidebar show only for admin role.

<ul class="nav nav-stacked nav-pills">
    <ui:fragment rendered="#{securityBean.admin}" >
        <li><h:link class="btn btn-primary" 
                    outcome="/admin/customerList"> 
                Customer List (Admin Only)
            </h:link> </li>
    </ui:fragment>
    <li><h:link class="btn btn-primary" 
                value="Show Emails (Member)" 
                outcome="/member/emailList" /></li>
</ul>

Step Test your application.
Login with mary with password 1234. The customer list and email list links should show in the navigation bar and the left sidebar.
